Genealogy Database of William (Bill) F. Archer

 

Organized by George W. Archer,

(George W. Archer is William F. Archers 5th cousin, once removed)

 

William (Bill) Forrest Archer was born 10 July 1926 in Woodsfield, OH to Frederick Herman Archer (1897-1952) and Hildred Magdalena Armbruster (1905- ?). Bills grandfather, Michael Francis Archer (1869-1949) was the owner and operator of a large grain mill located one block from the Woodsfield, OH Courthouse. The grain mill was one of the major landmarks in the village for many years. George Archer assembled a brief biographical sketch of Bill Archer that he called Introduction. This Introduction is included on this CD see the list of hyperlinks below.

Bill Archer was interested in genealogy and conducted research on his extended family lines over a period of about 30 years. He died 20 April 2004 from complications of diabetes before he could assemble his life-long genealogical collection into a coherent product. George W. Archer, 5th cousin of Bill Archer, once removed, rescued Bills genealogical collection from disposal and invested considerable effort into photographing over 3,500 pages of records, letters, photographs, funeral books and the like. One of Georges major contributions was to catalog the over 19,000 individuals in 2,600 surnames/ family names making up Bills research. The index of this correlation can be found in a document that George called Index. In this Index each of the 19,000+ individuals are listed. Following each name, the number of a photo(s) that somehow relates to that individual can be found.

 

Bills genealogy collection contains a treasure-trove of information and insight that can be invaluable to researchers of the family lines and individuals he investigated. Although this material remained largely disorganized, George Archer managed to assemble much of it into useful nuggets that lend themselves for research and discovery.

 

Below is a list of names included in the 3,500 photos and pages of this collection. These pages include a large collection of pictures of many of the ancestors. Names in all capital letters are the family names (surnames). Given names of each family are listed below their surnames.
